===========================================================================

Early release binaries for Oracle's JDK 9:
https://jdk9.java.net/download/
See below for how to install from there.
It sometimes takes a while for releases to show up at http://openjdk.java.net/install/

===========================================================================

Installing Java 8 JDK from Amazon Coretto
(Not necessary on Ubuntu which has up-to-date JDK 8 installed.)

# Get version number from https://docs.aws.amazon.com/corretto/latest/corretto-8-ug/downloads-list.html
MAJORVER=8
VER=8.222.10.1
cd ~/java
wget https://d3pxv6yz143wms.cloudfront.net/$VER/amazon-corretto-$VER-linux-x64.tar.gz
tar xf amazon-corretto-$VER-linux-x64.tar.gz
ln -sf amazon-corretto-$VER-linux-x64 amazon-corretto-$MAJORVER

...

===========================================================================

Source code via Mercurial:

# Java 8:
mkdir -p ~/java
cd ~/java/
hg clone http://hg.openjdk.java.net/jdk8/jdk8 openjdk8
cd openjdk8 && sh ./get_source.sh

# Java 9:
mkdir -p ~/java
cd ~/java/
hg clone http://hg.openjdk.java.net/jdk9/jdk9 openjdk9
# This gets all the parts of the JDK, which I probably don't need:
cd openjdk9 && sh ./get_source.sh

# Now, compile it (why do I want/need to do that?):
#if Ubuntu:
sudo apt install -y libX11-dev libxext-dev libxrender-dev libxtst-dev libxt-dev libcups2-dev libfreetype6-dev libasound2-dev ccache
#endif
bash ./configure
make all

===========================================================================

JDK 7 problems:
 * With recent JDK (eg, b104):
    * Randoop tests fail (in crontab only, not from the shell)
    * Javarifier tests fail on godwit but not on laptop.
 * With older JDK (eg, b92):
    * Hudson job jsr308-langtools-basic fails

===========================================================================

Ubuntu:

Nothing to do, because apt seems to have already installed it.
(Still Java 7 as of 8/2014.)

===========================================================================

JDK 9 (OpenJDK):

Two techniques: mercurial or download

----------------

## Mercurial (for source code):
# No need to do this; my other instructions made a ~/java/jdk-openjdk/.

----------------

## Note that this may intermittently fail, especially on a Thursday when
## Oracle is updating the weekly build.

## Download:
# See https://jdk.java.net/9/ to set these environment variables.
export OJDKMAJORVER="9"
# export OJDKBUILDNO="135"
export OJDKBUILDNO="167"
## "fcs" before official release, "ea" afterward (and the build number resets)
export EA="ea"
# export EA="fcs"
export OJDKVERSION=${OJDKBUILDNO}-linux-x64-${OJDKDATE}

export JDKPARENTDIR=$HOME/java/
mkdir -p $JDKPARENTDIR
cd $JDKPARENTDIR
rm -f jdk1.9.0
rm -f jdk-9

wget http://www.java.net/download/java/jdk${OJDKMAJORVER}/archive/${OJDKBUILDNO}/binaries/jdk-${OJDKMAJORVER}-${EA}+${OJDKBUILDNO}_linux-x64_bin.tar.gz
tar xzf jdk-${OJDKMAJORVER}-${EA}+${OJDKBUILDNO}_linux-x64_bin.tar.gz
mv jdk-${OJDKMAJORVER} jdk-${OJDKMAJORVER}-${EA}+${OJDKBUILDNO} 
ln -s jdk-${OJDKMAJORVER}-${EA}+${OJDKBUILDNO} jdk-${OJDKMAJORVER}
ln -s jdk-${OJDKMAJORVER} jdk${OJDKMAJORVER}
## Optional:
# rm -f jdk
# ln -s jdk1.${OJDKMAJORVER}.0 jdk
mkdir jdk-${OJDKMAJORVER}/src
# This src.zip file contains files that are not in the source bundle nor in
# the repository at http://hg.openjdk.java.net/jdk9/jdk9, for example
# java.io.FileDescriptor.  (Why?)
(cd jdk-${OJDKMAJORVER}/src; unzip -q ../src.zip)

### JDK docs (the date might be a day off!)
export JDKDOCDIR=$HOME/java/jdk-${OJDKMAJORVER}
mkdir -p $JDKDOCDIR
cd $JDKDOCDIR
# wget http://www.java.net/download/jdk${OJDKMAJORVER}/archive/${OJDKBUILDNO}/binaries/jdk-${OJDKMAJORVER}-docs-all.zip
# unzip -q jdk-${OJDKMAJORVER}-docs-all.zip
wget http://www.java.net/download/java/jdk${OJDKMAJORVER}/archive/${OJDKBUILDNO}/binaries/jdk-${OJDKMAJORVER}_doc-api-spec.tar.gz
tar xzf jdk-${OJDKMAJORVER}_doc-api-spec.tar.gz
# Only necessary once ever: cd ~/java; ln -s jdk/docs jdk-docs; ln -s jdk-${OJDKMAJORVER} jdk${OJDKMAJORVER}; ln -s jdk${OJDKMAJORVER} jdk
javadoc-index-to-alist > ~/.javadoc-index.el

===========================================================================

JDK 8 (OpenJDK):

For compilation, I should just install the JSR 308 compiler instead.
(But, that's just the compiler, not all of OpenJDK.)

Two techniques: mercurial or download

----------------

## Mercurial (for source code):
# No need to do this; my other instructions made a ~/java/jdk-openjdk/.

----------------

## Note that this may intermittently fail, especially on a Thursday when
## Oracle is updating the weekly build.

# On 1/8/2009 at CSE, running this yielded an installation that didn't seem
# to work for me.  In particular, running
#   java -jar $inv/java/lookup.jar
# yielded
#   Exception in thread "main" java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: com/sun/javadoc/RootDoc
# even though tools.jar was on the classpath.  Switching the symbolic link
# back to JDK6 permitted me to run the program.

## Newer:
# See https://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/index.html
mkdir $HOME/java/jdk1.8.0_212
cd $HOME/java
wget https://d3pxv6yz143wms.cloudfront.net/8.212.04.2/amazon-corretto-8.212.04.2-linux-x64.tar.gz


## Download:
# See http://jdk.java.net/8/ to set these environment variables.
export OJDKMAJORVER="8"
export OJDKUPDATEVER="152"
export OJDKVER=${OJDKMAJORVER}u${OJDKUPDATEVER}
export OJDKBUILDNO="b03"
export OJDKDATE="19_apr_2017"
## "fcs" before official release, "ea" afterward (and the build number resets)
export EA="ea"
# export EA="fcs"
export OJDKVERSION=${OJDKBUILDNO}-linux-x64-${OJDKDATE}
export JDKPARENTDIR=$HOME/java/
mkdir -p $JDKPARENTDIR
cd $JDKPARENTDIR
wget http://www.java.net/download/java/jdk$OJDKVER/archive/${OJDKBUILDNO}/binaries/jdk-$OJDKVER-${EA}-bin-${OJDKVERSION}.tar.gz
tar xzf jdk-$OJDKVER-${EA}-bin-${OJDKVERSION}.tar.gz
mv jdk1.8.0_${OJDKUPDATEVER} jdk1.8.0_${OJDKUPDATEVER}-${OJDKBUILDNO}
ln -s jdk1.8.0_${OJDKUPDATEVER}-${OJDKBUILDNO} jdk1.8.0_${OJDKUPDATEVER}
rm -f jdk1.8.0
ln -s jdk1.8.0_${OJDKUPDATEVER} jdk1.8.0
ln -s jdk1.8.0 jdk8
## Optional:
# rm -f jdk
# ln -s jdk1.8.0 jdk
mkdir jdk1.8.0/src
# This src.zip file contains files that are not in the source bundle nor in
# the repository at http://hg.openjdk.java.net/jdk8/jdk8, for example
# java.io.FileDescriptor.  (Why?)
(cd jdk1.8.0/src; unzip -q ../src.zip)

### JDK 8 docs (the date might be a day off!)
export JDKDOCDIR=$HOME/java/jdk1.8.0
cd $JDKDOCDIR
## This does not seem to exist for JDK 8 builds
## Download the file by going to
## http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/index.html
## and following links at "Java SE 8 Documentation".
mv ~/tmp/jdk-8u*-docs-all.zip .
unzip -q jdk-8u*-docs-all.zip
# Only necessary once ever: cd ~/java; ln -s jdk/docs jdk-docs; ln -s jdk1.8.0 jdk8; ln -s jdk8 jdk
javadoc-index-to-alist > ~/.javadoc-index.el

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

For MacOS X:

JDK 8 at:
http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/jdk8-downloads-2133151.html

Execute
/usr/libexec/java_home
and link that to ~/java/jdk[XXX],
then link that to ~/java/jdk

I also need the documentation from:
http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/documentation/jdk8-doc-downloads-2133158.html
mv ~/tmp/jdk-8u25-docs-all.zip ~/java/
cd ~/java
unzip jdk-8u25-docs-all.zip
ln -s docs jdk-docs

-----

Older:

# Need Mac OS X 10.5 to compile (Mac OS X 10.4 doesn't work), so get binary
# distribution:

OpenJDK Darwin i386 binaries (linked from http://landonf.bikemonkey.org/):
wget http://landonf.bikemonkey.org/static/soylatte/openjdk/openjdk8-darwin-i386-20080820.tar.bz2


